\section*{Introduction}
Teaching methodologies have evolved significantly with the advent of technology. This document compares the methodologies used in \textbf{virtual} and \textbf{conventional classroom settings}, highlighting their \textbf{similarities}, \textbf{differences}, and the \textbf{advantages and disadvantages} of each in light of the unique variables inherent to both environments.

\section*{Similarities}
Both virtual and conventional classrooms share several fundamental goals and teaching methods:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Knowledge Delivery:} Teachers in both settings aim to impart knowledge to students.
    \item \textbf{Student Engagement:} Encouraging student participation is a common objective.
    \item \textbf{Assessment:} Both environments require evaluation methods such as tests, quizzes, and projects.
    \item \textbf{Communication:} Interaction between teachers and students is essential in both contexts.
\end{itemize}

\section*{Differences}
The key differences between virtual and conventional classrooms lie in the \textbf{mode of delivery}, \textbf{interactivity}, \textbf{environment}, and \textbf{logistics}.

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Delivery Mode:}
    - \textit{Conventional}: Face-to-face interaction with physical presence.
    - \textit{Virtual}: Asynchronous and/or synchronous delivery via digital platforms.

    \item \textbf{Interactivity:}
    - \textit{Conventional}: High interactivity through eye contact, body language, and immediate feedback.
    - \textit{Virtual}: Limited interactivity due to technical constraints, but enhanced via chat, forums, and breakout rooms.
